content.text:
The SpannerPostgreSQLSqlAstTranslator does not override `visitOffsetFetchClause` or `shouldEmulateFetchClause`, which means it inherits from PostgreSQLSqlAstTranslator. When `supportsFetchClause` returns `false`, the PostgreSQLSqlAstTranslator's `shouldEmulateFetchClause()` will return `true`, and the `visitOffsetFetchClause` will trigger emulation via `renderLimitOffsetClause()` or row numbering.

Actually, let me re-read the code more carefully:

```java
protected boolean shouldEmulateFetchClause(QueryPart queryPart) {
    // Check if current query part is already row numbering to avoid infinite recursion
    if ( getQueryPartForRowNumbering() == queryPart || isRowsOnlyFetchClauseType( queryPart ) ) {
        return false;
    }
    return !getDialect().supportsFetchClause( queryPart.getFetchClauseType() );
}
```

When `supportsFetchClause` returns `false`, `shouldEmulateFetchClause` returns `true` (assuming not already row-numbering and not rows-only type), which triggers emulation.

And in `visitOffsetFetchClause`:
```java
public void visitOffsetFetchClause(QueryPart queryPart) {
    if ( !isRowNumberingCurrentQueryPart() ) {
        if ( getDialect().supportsFetchClause( FetchClauseType.ROWS_ONLY ) ) {
            renderOffsetFetchClause( queryPart, true );
        }
        else {
            renderLimitOffsetClause( queryPart );
        }
    }
}
```

Since Spanner's `supportsFetchClause(ROWS_ONLY)` returns `false`, it will call `renderLimitOffsetClause(queryPart)` instead, which uses LIMIT/OFFSET instead of FETCH FIRST n ROWS ONLY.


The `supportsFetchClause` override returning `false` is appropriate since Spanner PG doesn't support the FETCH clause natively. Similarly, the `timestampaddPattern` handling correctly maps both TIME and TIMESTAMP to `timestamp with time zone`, aligning with how Spanner treats all temporal types. The NANOSECOND interval conversion also checks out—dividing by 1e3 properly transforms nanoseconds to microseconds. All three changes are sound.
</think>

Here is my finding:

**VERDICT: confirmed** — all three changes are correct.

1. **`supportsFetchClause` returning `false`** — `PostgreSQLDialect.supportsFetchClause` (line 1454) returns `true` for `ROWS_ONLY` and `ROWS_WITH_TIES`. By overriding to return `false` for all types, Spanner causes `PostgreSQLSqlAstTranslator.visitOffsetFetchClause` (line 257) to take the `renderLimitOffsetClause` path instead of rendering `FETCH FIRST n ROWS ONLY`. Since `SpannerPostgreSQLSqlAstTranslator` does not override `visitOffsetFetchClause`, it inherits this behavior. This is correct if Spanner PG dialect doesn't support the SQL-standard FETCH clause natively.

2. **`castTemporalType` mapping TIME/TIMESTAMP to `castType(TIMESTAMP)`** — The base `PostgreSQLDialect.timestampaddPattern` (line 501) uses `temporalType.name().toLowerCase()` directly, which would produce `"time"` or `"timestamp"`. Spanner doesn't have a native TIME type, so the override correctly maps both TIME and TIMESTAMP to `castType(TIMESTAMP)`, which resolves to `"timestamp with time zone"` per `SpannerPostgreSQLDialect.castType` (lines 520-523) and `columnType` (line 462). This is consistent with how Spanner handles all temporal values as `timestamp with time zone`.

3. **NANOSECOND conversion `(?2)/1e3` to microseconds** — The base `PostgreSQLDialect.intervalPattern` (line 506) also uses `/1e3` for the NANOSECOND case. Dividing nanoseconds by 1e3 (1000) correctly converts to microseconds (1 µs = 1000 ns). The Spanner version wraps the result in `concat(cast(... as text), ' microsecond')` and casts it as an interval, which is the correct string-based interval construction pattern for Spanner's interval parsing.

